         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>säm</w><w>nu</w><w>pras<supplied>e</supplied>n<supplied>a</supplied>ji</w><w>wäl<surplus>ä</surplus></w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>ṣä</supplied>pnäṣ</w><w>wārpat</w><w>ptāñäkte</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a3"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>räṣ</w><w>prasenaji</w><w>wä<supplied>l</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>rä</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="3"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="2"/><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>t</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>sam</w><w>mätne</w><w>ceṣ</w><w>brā<supplied>hmnāñ</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>wä</supplied>tkāṣäl</w><pc>॥</pc><w>täm</w><w>kaklyu<supplied>ṣuräṣ</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>näṃ</w><w><supplied>kn</supplied>ānm<supplied>u</supplied>nyo</w><w>mät<supplied>t</supplied>ak</w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... king Prasenajit ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he urged [him] from [his] sleep (?). ... of the Buddha ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having ..., king Prasenajit ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... so these brahmins ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... may be answered. || Having heard this ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... through the wisdom, he himself ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">In one frame with <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1483b"/>. Since the fragment is damaged in the same way as <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1483b"/>, the two fragments must have been lying on each other.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment"><hi>/// säm</hi>: A reading <hi>säm</hi> requires a construction <hi>säm prasenaji wäl</hi> 'this king Prasenajit'; a reading <hi>(ce)säm</hi> requires heavy object fronting.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>(ṣä)pnäṣ</hi>: <hi>pnäṣ</hi> could theoretically also be a verb form, cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a29"/> b2 <hi>pnäṣṣ-äṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>sam</hi>: Since <hi>mätne</hi> probably starts a clause, <hi>sam</hi> probably ends a clause. Therefore, it is more likely to be a 1sg. verb form than the word 'same'.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><distinct type="ms_text">_m _m_a</distinct>: the first <distinct type="ms_text">_m</distinct> seems to be connected to the left so that it would be virāma position, but at the same time there is a second <distinct type="ms_text">_m</distinct>, which makes a ligature reading more likely.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment"><hi>(wä)tkāṣäl</hi>: the akṣara traces before <hi>tkā</hi> are compatible with <hi>w</hi>, but not with e.g. <hi>pyu</hi> (cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1378e"/> b1 <hi>pyutkāṣäl</hi>).</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment"><hi>näṃ</hi>: If a spelling <hi>tsäṃ</hi> without Fremdzeichen is admitted (cf. in particular <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht3976"/> a3), a reading <hi>(tsopa)t(s)äṃ</hi> (cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a278"/> b3) could also be possible.</note></p>
         </div>
